entry.title: Separate methods for fetching manifests and segments for EXT-X-MAP
entry.content:
The EXT-X-MAP tag allows a manifest to declare the URI/range of a

leading chunk of data which should be prefixed to every sequence of

media segments declared later in the file. As a result of this,

each media segment may need to fetch multiple URI/range pairs in

order to parse properly. This is especially common for fragmented

mp4 content, where the mp4 headers are stored at a single URI, and

content is fragmented across other URIs.



This CL separates HlsRenditionHost::ReadFromUrl into two methods:

HlsRenditionHost::StreamManifest

HlsRenditionHost::StreamMediaSegment



which allows constructing the proper queue of segments for a media

segment fetch, while keeping a simple interface for streaming a

manifest.

entry.title: Reapply "IDB: add/improve some performance metrics."
entry.content:
This reverts commit ce1ab8f3aac6d2f02bbb1ddb1df189ab18d2d2f7.



Change to original: make browser test wait for transaction commit

before calling `done()`. Without this step, the browser side

verifications are racy.



Original change's description:

> IDB: add/improve some performance metrics.

>

> The long-existing Transaction.*.TimeActive metric starts measuring from

> when a transaction "starts" and stops measuring when it's half way

> through committing, i.e. when done writing blobs (if any), but not done

> with the LevelDB commit. Not clear if this was intentional, but it's

> being replaced by `TimeActive2` which measures until after the LevelDB

> commit finishes, which should better capture differences between

> backing stores (e.g. LevelDB vs SQLite) as well as the effects of

> relaxed durability.

>

> A new renderer metric is added that measures the time taken to open a

> database, which can either be establishing a new connection to an

> existing database or creating a new database. This is an important

> aspect of read performance which the `ObjectStoreGet` metric fails to

> measure since it doesn't start measuring until the transaction is

> already active. `open` delays could be affected by IDB thread

> contention (crbug.com/1474996) or database lock contention, i.e.

> those resources guarded by PartitionedLockManager; relaxing

> durability should generally shorten the duration for which locks are

> held, so hopefully this metric demonstrates a difference in that

> experiment.

>

> A new browser metric, Transaction.*.TimeQueued, measures the time

> spent in the transaction queue before starting. Like the new renderer

> metric, this should capture "traffic jams" from lock or thread

> contention.

>

entry.title: Implement Multi-URL data source streams for EXT-X-MAP implementation
entry.content:
The EXT-X-MAP tag allows a manifest to declare the URI/range of a

leading chunk of data which should be prefixed to every media segment

declared later in the file. As a result of this, each media segment may

need to fetch multiple URI/range pairs in order to parse properly. This

is especially common for fragmented mp4 content, where the mp4 headers

are stored at a single URI, and content is fragmented across other URIs.



This first CL modifies HLSDataSourceProvider to accept a queue of

URI/Range segments instead of a single URI and range. There are no

changes to the current use of HlsDataSourceProvider, which will come in

subsequent CLs.



R=dalecurtis

entry.title: [AsyncSB] Show interstitial in AsyncCheckTracker when UrlCheckerOnSB completes.
entry.content:
AsyncCheckTracker will show an interstitial if the check is completed

between BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle::WillProcessResponse and

WebContentsObserver::DidFinishNavigation. When the complete callback

from UrlCheckerOnSB is called, AsyncCheckTracker will cache the

result and wait for DidFinishNavigation to be called. When

DidFinishNavigation is called, AsyncCheckTracker will trigger a

warning via BaseUIManager::DisplayBlockingPage.



The information of post commit error message will be added in

UrlCheckerOnSB::OnCompleteCheckResult in a follow up CL.



Code references:

1) The check on the severest threat is from

SafeBrowsingNavigationThrottle::WillFailRequest[1].

2) Setting render_process_id and render_frame_token is from

ClientSideDetectionHost::MaybeShowPhishingWarning[2].



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/safe_browsing/content/browser/safe_browsing_navigation_throttle.cc;l=45;drc=2f1cf47e4272b96f848d0f25fd1ca3b08db01183

entry.title: v4l2/stateless: Move enqueue to surface reference destructor
entry.content:
There are two consumers of a buffer. The |StatelessDecodeSurface|

and the |VideoFrame|. Only when both are done with the buffer

can it be enqueued.



The |VideoFrame| destructor observer can not be the one

to enqueue the buffer because a |VideoFrame| is only constructed

on visible frames. Some codecs have non visible frames that are

used for reference.



The |StatelessDecodeSurface| enqueues on the destructor, but the

|VideoFrame| holds a reference. This prevents the enqueuing of

a buffer until both references are released. In the case of a

non visible frame there is no reference held by the |VideoFrame|

so it can be enqueued once all decoded frame references are

satisfied.

entry.title: Fix clipboard crash when reading files on Lacros.
entry.content:
The root problem is that multiple IPC clipboard calls are made in a row

and the actual clipboard state can change while that's happening, which

leads to a situation where the clipboard may fail to serve up types it

recently claimed to have had on offer.



This race should not in theory be limited to Lacros, but in practice I

suspect Lacros is doing something weird with the clipboard such as

modifying it in the background without user intervention.



The proximate cause is not checking the mojo smart pointer type for

nullness, which is how this patch addresses the issue. The paste will

still fail, but silently, which may be something for the CrOS team to

investigate.

use. This solves the issue of having multiple frames

but only one callback.

entry.title: Add a screen-ai CIPD package for PDF OCR E2E tests on Linux
entry.content:
To have E2E tests for PDF OCR on Windows, macOS, and Linux, we need to

be able to download and use the screen-ai library in those tests.

Pursuing this goal, we upload the screen-ai library for Linux to CIPD

and download it from CIPD to //third_party/screen-ai. This downloaded

library is then loaded in E2E tests (i.e. browser tests).



For more information, visit go/chrome_screen_ai_tests and read the

Uploading the library files to CIPD section.
